snippet.textDisplay:
In the defense of AI dungeon, it has the agenda of trying to tell you a story. I don't believe it failed your test, it just ignored it entirely. And that is something it occasionally does (ignore user input and do something else) even when not given a winograd schema test.


It would probably still fail at most of these tests, but not all of them. I have personally witnessed it recognizing what type of object certain words represent ("this object is food", "this other is a weapon", etc.) or remembering attributes about objects ("elf is dead", "this guy is a demon", etc.). It's not good at it, but it isn't entirely incapable either.

snippet.textDisplay: That’s not how I would approach solving Winograd schemas using GPT-2 or another ML language model. All those models work by estimating the probability of a given piece of text. Given a Winograd schema, I would substitute both possible solutions for the “it” pronoun and compare the resulting probabilities, then take the solution with a higher probability. I believe a modern language model will result in >50% correct solutions, though still below 100%.

snippet.textDisplay:
So all we machine got to learn is archetypes. The only reason machines don't think as humans is because we don't teach them our psychology. When I say table, you'll have some image and concept idea of a table. This idea is different but similar from what I see. You may see a white plastic table outdoors, someone else might see a huge wooden table in a mansion, someone else might see a living room table made from glass. Btw this is how misunderstandings happen, same words different mental meaning while everyone assumes everyone else thinks the same. So all we have to let machines have archetypal concepts of things and stuff. Further we will need a few very intelligent people to teach it how to have archetypes of peoples archetypes so they can tell which person is likely to think in one way over the other.

Now talking to such a machine you will have no idea it is a machine because not only does it know all you know and more, but also it will be able to articulate information in a pattern similar to how humans think. Since by speaking we broadcast our thought we are used to receiving information in the same format. If a machine would communicate and understand you in the same manner you think, we would think it has human level intelligence. Which may not be that great of an intelligence at all.

snippet.textDisplay: There's also no such thing as "too big" (as far as the suitcase is concerned) in the trophy/suitcase sentence. If it's big enough for the trophy, it's big enough for the trophy. Who cares if it's more than big enough? The only thing that makes sense for "it" to be referring to is the trophy, since there would be issues with the trophy being too big and the suitcase being too small.
